\section{Metadata access}{
\code{fit$metadata} is a closed list of 13 named fields; four
additional payloads are stored as attributes
(\code{diagnostics}, \code{diagnostic_skipped},
\code{sampler_diagnostics_failed}, \code{sd_g_summary}). The methods on this
page are the recommended access path: \code{summary()} surfaces the
user-relevant fields; \code{\link[=diagnose]{diagnose()}} returns a structured
\code{bef_diagnostic} object covering the diagnostic attributes; direct
\code{attr()} access is supported but unnecessary.
}

\section{Sites and labels}{
Site labels propagated from the input (named list or \code{escalc} row
names) appear in \code{coef()} names, \code{vcov()} dimnames, the \code{site}
column of \code{confint()} and \code{as.data.frame()}, and \code{summary()} print
output. When labels are absent the numeric site index is used.
}

\section{Print and format backends}{
\code{print()} and \code{format()} for \code{bef_fit}, \code{summary.bef_fit},
\code{bef_data}, and \code{bef_diagnostic} prefer \code{cli}-styled output when
the \code{cli} package is installed and stdout supports it, and fall
back to a plain base-R representation otherwise. The \code{use_cli}
argument lets callers force one branch:
\itemize{
\item \code{use_cli = NULL} (default) — auto-detect.
\item \code{use_cli = TRUE} — force \code{cli} styling (errors if \code{cli} is not
installed).
\item \code{use_cli = FALSE} — force plain base output.
}

Setting the environment variable \code{BAYESEFRON_NO_CLI=1} is
equivalent to \code{use_cli = FALSE} for every call in the session and
is the recommended way to suppress styling in CI logs and
redirected stdout.
}

\section{Site count requirement}{
The \code{bef_data} validator (used by \code{as_bef_data()} and
\code{bayes_efron_fit()}) requires at least five sites. The constraint
reflects the methodological requirement of the log-spline
deconvolution prior, not a software limitation.
}

